= Research

I work at the intersection of *power-system control theory*, *deep learning* (graph neural networks, *small / large language models --- sLM / LLM*), *IoT systems*, and *grid cybersecurity*. Most of my output focuses on time-series problems on energy and IoT data: forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection. Validation scales from textbook benchmarks to real PMU field data, with all training and inference run on dedicated multi-GPU servers I configure and maintain end-to-end.

== Research areas

- AI / sLM / LLM methods for power-system stability and smart-grid resilience
- Spectral reprogramming of frozen *small language models (sLM)* and LLMs for time-series tasks
- IoT and edge intelligence for distributed energy resources
- Multi-impairment communication-network co-design (delay, packet loss, jitter)
- Graph neural networks over electrical-grid topologies
- Federated learning and knowledge distillation across IoT-edge devices
- SCADA anomaly detection on real PMU field data
- Dual-domain (spectral + temporal) representation learning
- Dedicated GPU-server infrastructure: cluster provisioning, multi-GPU training, inference deployment

== Recent research --- *Smart-grid co-optimization with LLM-driven anomaly detection*

A unified co-optimization framework for smart-grid dispatch and communication routing with formal stability guarantees and *small-language-model (sLM)* based SCADA anomaly detection. The framework treats the grid as an *IoT-instrumented* system: PMU streams, edge gateways, and SCADA endpoints are first-class data sources. All training and inference run on a dedicated multi-GPU server in the YuLab. This is the active doctoral project (2025 onwards).

~~~
{}{raw}
<a class="inline-fig" href="/assets/phd/all.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img src="/assets/phd/all.png" alt="Doctoral framework — overview of the three pillars" loading="lazy" /></a>
~~~

=== Three pillars

. *Formal delay-stability coupling bounds.* Closed-form stability bounds where delay-margin coupling is *learned* per generator from operational data.
~~~
{}{raw}
<a class="inline-fig" href="/assets/phd/year1.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img src="/assets/phd/year1.png" alt="Year 1 — formal delay-stability coupling bounds" loading="lazy" /></a>
<details class="more"><summary>Method &amp; expected validation</summary>
<div class="more-body">
<p>Built on a <strong>dual-domain graph neural network</strong> operating jointly in the spectral domain (Laplacian eigenstructure of the grid) and the temporal domain (PMU time-series), producing per-generator coupling parameters whose physical interpretability is preserved by an additive decomposition.</p>
<p><strong>Expected validation targets.</strong> Stability margin error within 5% of analytical baselines on IEEE 14, 30, 57, 118-bus benchmarks; runtime under 200 ms per evaluation on a single workstation GPU.</p>
</div>
</details>
~~~
. *Multi-impairment stability analysis.* Generalises the delay-only bound to compound impairments (delay + packet loss + jitter), each as a physically interpretable additive component.
~~~
{}{raw}
<a class="inline-fig" href="/assets/phd/year2.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img src="/assets/phd/year2.png" alt="Year 2 — multi-impairment stability analysis" loading="lazy" /></a>
<details class="more"><summary>Method &amp; expected validation</summary>
<div class="more-body">
<p>A margin-erosion decomposition maps each impairment to an additive component with learned per-generator weights, enabling per-component sensitivity analysis without losing physical interpretability.</p>
<p><strong>Expected validation targets.</strong> Bound tightness under +/-20% impairment perturbation across 8 power-system benchmarks up to <strong>PEGASE 2,869-bus</strong>; full reproducibility on public OpenDSS and pandapower test cases.</p>
</div>
</details>
~~~
. *SLM-based SCADA anomaly prediction.* Predicts impairment trajectories from SCADA / PMU streams to trigger preventive dispatch before stability margins are breached.
~~~
{}{raw}
<a class="inline-fig" href="/assets/phd/year3.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img src="/assets/phd/year3.png" alt="Year 3 — sLM-based SCADA anomaly prediction" loading="lazy" /></a>
<details class="more"><summary>Method &amp; expected validation</summary>
<div class="more-body">
<p>Built on the spectrally-reprogrammed <strong>small-language-model (sLM)</strong> pipeline of Spec2LLM and LLM4Imp, operating on tokenised PMU windows from IoT-edge gateways. A control loop couples the prediction to the dispatch optimiser of pillar&nbsp;1. Inference is colocated on the same dedicated GPU server as training, with the aim of keeping latency under the 30&nbsp;s leading-time target.</p>
<p><strong>Expected validation targets.</strong> Anomaly leading-time of at least 30 s before the empirical instability threshold on real PMU field data, with a false-alarm rate under 5%.</p>
</div>
</details>
~~~

== Secondary track --- *Spectral reprogramming of language models for time-series*

A frozen language model --- *sLM* or LLM --- reprogrammed with frequency-domain prompts, generalises across forecasting, imputation and anomaly tasks on energy and *IoT time-series* without per-task fine-tuning. Training runs on dedicated GPU servers; the *sLM* variants are explicitly designed so inference can be deployed close to IoT-edge gateways.

- *Spec2Llama* --- /Expert Systems with Applications/, IF 7.5, JCR Q1, 2026.
- *Spec2LLM* --- IEEE ICCE 2026, Dubai.
- *LLM4Imp* --- IEEE ICC 2026, Glasgow.

~~~
{}{raw}
<details class="more"><summary>How the pipeline evolved</summary>
<div class="more-body">
<p><strong>Spec2Llama</strong> introduced the spectral-aware forecasting frame: time-series tokens are projected into a learned frequency representation that prompts a frozen Llama backbone, enabling versatile time-series analysis across heterogeneous datasets without per-task fine-tuning.</p>
<p><strong>Spec2LLM</strong> applied the same idea to power-transformer temperature forecasting, with a tighter spectral-to-language token coupling and validation on grid-equipment monitoring data.</p>
<p><strong>LLM4Imp</strong> extended the pipeline to time-series imputation under heavy missing-data regimes (long gaps, irregular sampling) by reformulating imputation as a frequency-domain prompt completion task.</p>
<p>This pipeline is the foundation for pillar 3 of the doctoral project (SLM-based SCADA anomaly prediction).</p>
</div>
</details>
~~~

